<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,908,1293]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
A species-rich genus containing currently 35 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Uetz, P." box="[751,873,943,968]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" refId="ref67280" refString="Uetz, P. (2013) The Reptile database. Available from: http: // www. reptile-database. org / (accessed 8 July 2014)" type="url" year="2013">Uetz 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The distribution spans from E Europe to E 
<collectingCountry box="[1369,1436,943,968]" name="China" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">China</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[198,269,980,1003]" name="South Korea" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Korea</collectingCountry>
, most species occur in Central Asia, 
<collectingCountry box="[678,748,980,1005]" name="China" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">China</collectingCountry>
, and on the Iranian Plateau. The genus is traditionally divided into five subgenera as proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Szczerbak, N. N." box="[586,793,1015,1040]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" refId="ref66117" refString="Szczerbak, N. N. (1974) Palearctic lizards. Akademija Nauk Ukrainskoi S. S. R., Istitut Zoologii, Kiev, 296 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1974">Szczerbak (1974)</bibRefCitation>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1834" box="[811,904,1016,1039]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[811,904,1016,1039]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Eremias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<taxonomicName authority=", Pareremias" authorityName="Pareremias" authorityYear="1928" box="[924,1249,1016,1039]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Ommateremias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ommateremias, Pareremias</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Lantz, 1928" authorityName="Lantz" authorityYear="1928" box="[1267,1432,1015,1040]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Rhabderemias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Rhabderemias</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Wiegmann, 1834" authorityName="Wiegmann" authorityYear="1834" box="[151,258,1052,1075]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Scapteira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Scapteira</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. This division is supported by the hemipenial morphology (
<bibRefCitation author="Arnold, E. N." box="[954,1119,1052,1077]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="1221 - 1257" refId="ref45776" refString="Arnold, E. N. (1986 b) The hemipenis of lacertid lizards: structure, variation and systematic implication. Journal of Natural History, 20, 1221 - 1257. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222938600770811" type="journal article" year="1986">Arnold 1986b</bibRefCitation>
), but species assignment to individual subgenera remains inconsistent (
<bibRefCitation author="Arnold, E. N." box="[636,798,1087,1112]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="1221 - 1257" refId="ref45776" refString="Arnold, E. N. (1986 b) The hemipenis of lacertid lizards: structure, variation and systematic implication. Journal of Natural History, 20, 1221 - 1257. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222938600770811" type="journal article" year="1986">Arnold 1986b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, S. C." box="[809,984,1087,1112]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" refId="ref45318" refString="Anderson, S. C. (1999) The lizards of Iran. Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles, Oxford, Ohio, 442 pp." type="book" year="1999">Anderson 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Guo, X. &amp; Dai, X. &amp; Chen, D. &amp; Papenfuss, T. J. &amp; Ananjeva, N. B. &amp; Melnikov, D. A. &amp; Wang, Y." box="[995,1173,1087,1112]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="400 - 412" refId="ref52562" refString="Guo, X., Dai, X., Chen, D., Papenfuss, T. J., Ananjeva, N. B., Melnikov, D. A. &amp; Wang, Y. (2011) Phylogeny and divergence times of some racerunner lizards (Lacertidae: Eremias) inferred from mitochondrial 16 S rRNA gene segments. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 61, 400 - 412. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2011.06.022" type="journal article" year="2011">
Guo 
<emphasis box="[1050,1107,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, 
<taxonomicName authority="Wiegmann, 1834" authorityName="Wiegmann" authorityYear="1834" box="[1329,1436,1088,1111]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Scapteira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1329,1436,1088,1111]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scapteira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lantz, 1928" authorityName="Lantz" authorityYear="1928" box="[199,361,1124,1149]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Rhabderemias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,361,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Rhabderemias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were reconstructed as polyphyletic (
<bibRefCitation author="Guo, X. &amp; Dai, X. &amp; Chen, D. &amp; Papenfuss, T. J. &amp; Ananjeva, N. B. &amp; Melnikov, D. A. &amp; Wang, Y." box="[776,958,1124,1149]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="400 - 412" refId="ref52562" refString="Guo, X., Dai, X., Chen, D., Papenfuss, T. J., Ananjeva, N. B., Melnikov, D. A. &amp; Wang, Y. (2011) Phylogeny and divergence times of some racerunner lizards (Lacertidae: Eremias) inferred from mitochondrial 16 S rRNA gene segments. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 61, 400 - 412. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2011.06.022" type="journal article" year="2011">
Guo 
<emphasis box="[834,891,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
). Many phylogenetic studies failed to find sister group to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1834" box="[341,434,1160,1183]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[341,434,1160,1183]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Eremias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genus was recognized as a part of a clade containing the Palearctic genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1834" box="[151,338,1196,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Acanthodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,338,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Acanthodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1838" box="[352,456,1196,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Mesalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[352,456,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Mesalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lutz, Bischoff &amp; Mayer" authorityYear="1986" box="[470,616,1196,1219]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Omanosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[470,616,1196,1219]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Omanosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Menetries" authorityYear="1832" box="[672,778,1196,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Ophisops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[672,778,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Ophisops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Sub-Saharan 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sternfeld" authorityYear="1912" box="[1025,1110,1196,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Adolfus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1025,1110,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Adolfus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1165,1265,1196,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Holaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1165,1265,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Holaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of both morphological and genetic data (
<bibRefCitation author="Arnold, E. N." box="[571,718,1231,1256]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="209 - 257" refId="ref45822" refString="Arnold, E. N. (1989) Toward a phylogeny and biogeography of the Lacertidae: relationships within an Old-World family of lizards derived from morphology. Bulletin of the British Museum (Zoology), 55, 209 - 257." type="journal article" year="1989">Arnold 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mayer, W. &amp; Pavlicev, M." box="[729,999,1231,1256]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="1155 - 1163" refId="ref58209" refString="Mayer, W. &amp; Pavlicev, M. (2007) The phylogeny of the family Lacertidae (Reptilia) based on nuclear DNA sequences: Convergent adaptations to arid habitats within the subfamily Eremiainae. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 44, 1155 - 1163. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2007.05.015" type="journal article" year="2007">Mayer &amp; Pavlicev 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hipsley, C. A. &amp; Himmelmann, L. &amp; Metzler, D. &amp; Muller, J." box="[1009,1225,1231,1256]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="151" refId="ref53389" refString="Hipsley, C. A., Himmelmann, L., Metzler, D. &amp; Muller, J. (2009) Integration of Bayesian molecular clock methods and fossilbased soft bounds reveals early Cenozoic origin of African lacertid lizards. BMC Evolutionary Biology, 9, 151. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1186 / 1471 - 2148 - 9 - 151" type="journal article" year="2009">
Hipsley 
<emphasis box="[1102,1158,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
). Latest phylogeny of all squamate reptiles (
<bibRefCitation author="Pyron, R. &amp; Burbrink, F. &amp; Wiens, J." box="[426,622,1268,1293]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="93" refId="ref62209" refString="Pyron, R., Burbrink, F. &amp; Wiens, J. (2013) A phylogeny and revised classification of Squamata, including 4161 species of lizards and snakes. BMC Evolutionary Biology, 13, 93. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1186 / 1471 - 2148 - 13 - 93" type="journal article" year="2013">
Pyron 
<emphasis box="[501,558,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
) recovered 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1834" box="[754,847,1269,1292]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[754,847,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Eremias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a sister to the South African lacertids.
</paragraph>
